;; =============================================================================
;; Triangle Inequality Testing - Demonstrating Current Limitations
;; =============================================================================
;;
;; The ACTUAL triangle inequality is:
;;   dist(A,B) + dist(B,C) >= dist(A,C)
;;   OR: sqrt(dist2(A,B)) + sqrt(dist2(B,C)) >= sqrt(dist2(A,C))
;;
;; However, Hasclid does NOT support sqrt operations, so we cannot express this!
;;
;; What we CAN test is the SQUARED version:
;;   dist2(A,B) + dist2(B,C) >= dist2(A,C)
;;
;; BUT THIS IS NOT THE SAME as the triangle inequality!
;; It is FALSE for collinear points.
;; =============================================================================

;; -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
;; Test 1: Concrete collinear points - squared version should be REJECTED
;; -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:point A 0 0
:point B 1 0
:point C 2 0

;; For collinear points: A=(0,0), B=(1,0), C=(2,0)
;; dist2(A,B) = 1, dist2(B,C) = 1, dist2(A,C) = 4
;; Sum of squared: 1 + 1 = 2 < 4 ✗
;; So this should NOT be proved:
(>= (+ (dist2 A B) (dist2 B C)) (dist2 A C))
;; Expected: NOT PROVED (counterexample found)

;; -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
;; Test 2: Non-collinear triangle - squared version might still be false!
;; -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:point P 0 0
:point Q 3 0
:point R 0 4

;; For right triangle: P=(0,0), Q=(3,0), R=(0,4)
;; dist2(P,Q) = 9, dist2(Q,R) = 25, dist2(P,R) = 16
;; Sum of squared: 9 + 25 = 34 > 16 ✓
;; This happens to be true for this triangle
(>= (+ (dist2 P Q) (dist2 Q R)) (dist2 P R))
;; Expected: Might be PROVED (true for this specific case)

;; -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
;; Test 3: Symbolic 2D triangle - squared version
;; -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
:point A1
:point B1
:point C1

;; This is asking: For ALL triangles, is dist2(A,B) + dist2(B,C) >= dist2(A,C)?
;; Answer: NO! (collinear counterexample)
(>= (+ (dist2 A1 B1) (dist2 B1 C1)) (dist2 A1 C1))
;; Expected: NOT PROVED (correctly rejects invalid inequality)

;; =============================================================================
;; CONCLUSION:
;; =============================================================================
;;
;; 1. Hasclid correctly REJECTS the squared distance inequality for symbolic points
;;    (because it's mathematically false)
;;
;; 2. To prove the ACTUAL triangle inequality, we would need:
;;    a) sqrt operation in the parser
;;    b) Support for sqrt in the expression system
;;    c) CAD or another solver that can handle sqrt constraints
;;
;; 3. Alternative approaches:
;;    a) Add sqrt as a primitive operation
;;    b) Use the squared form but add non-collinearity constraint
;;    c) Reformulate using squared inequality (different theorem)
;;
;; =============================================================================
